		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Las Vegas, Nevada - March 2005<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045'>Patrick "Patrick M. S" Sullivan</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 6, 2006</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> Note from me: Hey all, I’d been meaning to do this for sometime now. I wanted to move all my Tournament Reports from the Decipher and DGMA sites to Decktech and Gameplayersnetwork since they are easier to find here and I’m worried that Decipher’s two sites will go down eventually. I wouldn’t want to lose all these awesome memories. So here they are, archived, for your amusement. Feel free to give reviews with your thoughts and memories of the events or to simply let me know how you liked the read. <br />
<br />
Mr. Sullivan goes to Vegas... again<br />
Las Vegas PSE Tournament Report<br />
Thursday, March 10th – Sunday, March 13th<br />
<br />
Pre-Tourney Jank<br />
<br />
Well the last time we left off, dear reader, I was getting back from nabbing a 2nd place finish at the World Cup in Essen, Germany. My, how time flies. I didn’t bother going to France in December for their PSE since with a bit of cost-benefit analysis, it didn’t make much sense. However, perhaps I should have since I was far closer to getting 2004 DGMA Player of the Year than I thought. I ended up pretty happy with my 4th place finish in that rat race (2nd in North America) so I extent warm congrats to Josh for earning that title. Nice job there, sports-fan.<br />
<br />
So what’s happened since Essen? Shadows, for starters. I have to say it’s taken me far longer to adapt to this new base set (with new rules) than previous times. However, I think I’ve got the swing of things what with site manipulation and all. I’m quite pleased that time limits have been extended to 60 minutes so I can say, at this point in time, that I’m confident I’ll be avoiding any timed losses at this particular PSE (knock on wood).<br />
<br />
Considering there is no cash prize for Lord of the Rings, you might be asking why I would choose to embark on such a silly journey? Well, in February I spent all my fan dollars on travel vouchers, an iPod and convention badges for this year. Those travel vouchers are the best thing since sliced bread. They can be used for air travel anywhere in the world or even for a cruise! Therefore the trip could certainly pay for itself as well as many other little excursions in the future. If I want real hard cold hot steamy cash, then there’s always the Texas Hold Em tables or Blackjack tables. As long as I don’t pull a Kenneth Ellingsen, I might actually walk away with something.<br />
<br />
However, the real reason why this Vegas trip was a no-brainer when I was asked to go is because my friend and fellow dAgent and DGMA judge, Kirk England, is getting married in Vegas! Him and his soon bride-to-be, Heather will be wed on Thursday, March 10th so my plane better arrive on time in the early afternoon since I have to go to the chapel (which, believe it or not, is called The Wee Kirk O’er the Heather) with the groom and best-man, then steal the rental car and get back to the hotel to change into my tux and grab the bride since I’m playing the common dual roles of Usher and Maid of Honour. This should be good fun.<br />
<br />
So that should be a fun evening of debauchery and such which should get my spirits up for the LotR games which begin on Friday (PSQ, Black Rider release). So onto LotR, the main deck I’m bringing for this occasion and intend to play with in the PSE is a fun Gandalf/Gollum deck. Gandalf sets up a killer fellowship with 3 or 4 Saved from the Fire (I still can’t decide how many to play). It’s a Fellowship that can triple move with ease given it’s high strength companions and skirmish-winning events. The Saved from the Fires also serve to increase the shadow/free-people’s ratio of cards in my draw deck since my shadow is just a TAD combo intensive. It plays Gollum with very few other minions that serves to either corrupt or outwound depending on the fellowship I’m up against. I’m also having trouble deciding how many Horribly Strong (great new Gollum culture Shadows card that my opponents will grow to Hate) I should play with. Right now I have one in the deck since I use it as a surprise but I’m thinking of putting 3 more in there and use it as a serious weapon. The fun thing about this shadow, and this is key, is that pretty much all the cards can be played in the shadow phase. Which means that I don’t necessarily have to have any minions left at the end of the shadow phase. That would bring us directly to the regroup phase which would frustrate a fellowship that plays lots of events of either a Maneuver, Archery or Skirmish nature. Since my fellowship triple moves, if I can get to site 6 before my opponent gets to site 5, then this is the strategy I shall employ. Offer no shadow resistance to my opponent’s fellowship since I’ll be making it to site 9 first and unchallenged. If they make it to site 5 before I make it to 6, then they can double to 7 and put unwanted pressure so I’ll have to take my shadow win a little more seriously. But hopefully that won’t happen. <br />
<br />
My fellowship can set up completely by site 3 if I get a Saved from the Fire in my opening (or mulliganed) hand and then draw into either another one or Barliman for site 2 or 3. I can’t afford to bid since G for Grand would become useless so I’ll probably end up going second which is fine by me. I’m sure I’ll outrun later. So my ideal fellowship consists of Frodo with Sting (Bane) and There and Back Again with a Tale of Great Ring sitting behind him. I’ll quickly burn Gandalf, Leader of Men and then the Forest Guardian to fetch Leader of the Company, Sent Back, Treebeard, Erland and Radagast. Gandalf will have his Staff and Glamdring, with Radagast sporting his Staff as well. Two G for Grands seems to be plenty and then we’re off to the races with a ton of events that I can draw into on my double and triple moves. Fun no? So far it’s been netting me some funky wins but we’ll see what happens when push comes to shove in the city of Lost Wages.<br />
<br />
<br />
Day 1 minus 2<br />
Thursday, March 10th, 2005<br />
Heather’s Wedding Day<br />
<br />
Right so after staying up until 1 in the morning try to get my weekly games in on a LotR Online Standard Constructed League, I have to get up at an ungodly hour of 5 in the morning to catch my flight. I don’t want to bring any winter clothes since I’m flying to the Nevada desert so I put on a light coat without gloves or a tuque (that’s Quebec talk for a Skully) into –30 degree weather. I park in the cheap parking which is almost half a mile from the airport entrance and there isn’t a shuttle bus in sight so I start walking quickly towards the departures area in the freezing cold. A shuttle bus drives by and I flag him down and he says he’s not servicing my parking lot. To which I reply, “Dude, look how I’m dressed! Let me on the friggin’ bus!!” To which he laughs and lets me own. Good thing for him since I was about to go all Bruce Banner on his bus. <br />
<br />
So I get into Philadelphia early for my connecting flight and decide to give myself a deck check so I don’t get nailed in the PSQ  the next day. I realize half way through that I should have done this at home since I don’t have any cards with me to rectify the situation. And sure enough, one of my two Shelobs (the foil one, of course) is missing. I kinda panic since I am playing with barely any minions in my deck and I need each and everyone. In fact, I had been playtesting my deck with 4 Shelobs for a while and slowly brought the number down to two which I had been slightly regretting. And now I only have ONE! So I call up Kirk England on my cell who was driving to Vegas and beg him to lend me a Shelob which he readily agrees to and saves me from an inevitable anxiety attack.<br />
<br />
I get on the plane and the movie is After the Sunset which is this terrible Pierce Brosman / Selma Hayek flick. So since earphones cost 5 bucks on U.S. Airways, I decide to forgo watching the movie and sleep most of the 5 hour flight. I should have brought something to read since I was bored out of my tree. Also food costs like 7 bucks so I passed on that since my wallet was in the overhead compartment and I was wedged into my window seat next to a couple of women who wouldn’t stop talking about craps strategy. <br />
<br />
So I arrive half an hour early in Vegas (read: 1h30 pm), pick up my luggage, call for a free shuttle to the Hampton Inn Tropicana and I arrive nice and early to check out the room and run into the Revolution crew (read: Steve Jones, Bryce Stevenson, Will Dineaga, Tim McKnight, Chris Cole) but my room is beside theirs with Paul Holbrook, Kirk England and his wife-in-about-6-hours-or-so, Heather. So I’m like totally starving at this point and try to get the guys to go get something to eat. Paul says that we’ll be eating after the wedding at 8pm so he says we should pass. But that’s like in 7 hours! So forget that noise, Kirk and I go to grab some Wendy’s to go. Big Bacon Classic Combo and I’m good for a few hours (try to pay attention to how much junk food I’m eating during this trip, I’m good to look like an American in no time if this keeps up). <br />
<br />
The boys then tell me that Kyle Craft and Tim McKnight are over at the Excalibur playing Texas Hold Em so since the wedding is so far away, I walk on over with Seth Maser and Emir Delic. The three of us sit down at a table and then I immediately switch so I can sit at Kyle’s 1-3 spread table. There is this one hand where Tim flops a straight and I’ve got pocket rockets with an ace on the flop. So Tim bets into me and I raise. The turn gives me my fourth ace and I’m one happy Canadian. So we re-raise for a while since Tim thinks that I’ve only got a set of Aces. So I smash down my aces after the river and say, “HIROSHIMA!” and take pretty much all of his money. He then proceeds to win most of it back by defeating me on each and every hand that we’re both involved in afterwards. I end up pretty much even. <br />
<br />
By the time I get back the groom, Kirk, his best man, Steve Jones and mock-Father of the Bride, Mike Noonan are all in their tuxedos so the four of us head down Las Vegas Boulevard (read: The Strip) to drive out to the Wee Kirk O’ The Heather wedding chapel at the end of the street. The drive takes much longer than we thought so I drop them off and I have ONE hour to get back, get changed and drive the bride and 3 others all the way back. The drive back to the hotel takes even longer and I’m freaking out on how I have 5 minutes to get a Tuxedo on. Luckily Paul Holbook is our resident expert at dressing (and undressing) men so he throws on the whole kit and caboodle in 3 minutes. <br />
<br />
We then race out of the hotel with Thomas Mitchell, his girlfriend, Pam, Paul Holbrook and the wedding dress-sporting Heather. Coming out of the parking lot I nearly drive straight into Bryce’s Expedition since it’s bigger than the Titanic (and even worse gas mileage) but we make it to the Chapel on time. <br />
<br />
It’s a nice little ceremony although Heather’s cell phone kept going off in my pocket. How embarrassing. The priest guy has one heck of an interesting accent and kept getting Kirk and Heather to repeat the same things twice cuz he kept forgetting where he was at in the ceremony. Pretty funny J<br />
<br />
We then all head back for a big feast at the Wild Wild West where we are slightly overdressed to say the least. I drink 4 Lemonades in about 5 minutes since I’m so thirsty and it nearly sends me into a diabetic seizure. I gotta cut down on the sugar-rich beverages. Then I’m pretty tired so I crash on the sofa-bed. What a day...<br />
<br />
<br />
Day Zero<br />
Friday, March 11th<br />
‘You think!?’<br />
<br />
So Kirk and Paul, being DGMA judges and all, have to get to the tournament hall by 9 or something so we get up early and go grab some MacDonald’s take out. I opt for Combo #9 which involves a Sausage McGriddle, Hash Brown and coffee. Pretty darn ‘tootin. <br />
<br />
I now have hours upon hours to kill so I walk on over to the Excalibur for more Texas Hold Em action. Now since the 1-3 spread tables don’t allow you to spin the cash wheel if you get your pocket rockets cracked or if you get dealt a four of a kind, I opt for the 3-6 spread table which ends up being much more fun since I can now bet enough to bluff. So I’m bluffing like crazy in the beginning and pick up a ton of small pots. I’m up more than 200$ after a couple hours when some guy at my table reads a shirt of a new arrival and says, “University of Toronto eh?” I look over and see Mike Ium who just arrived at my table. So I get up all excited to see him and give him a hug and such and bump into this chesty waitress who spills some of her drinks and gives me the stink eye. I barely notice and then Josh who just sat an a neighboring table says hi and I’m all excited to see him so I yell out, “hey man!” basically right in the waitress’s ear. Now she’s really pissed. So I give her a two dollar tip for my coffee and the guy in front of me says when she gave me the drink she looked really pissed off. Ah well. <br />
<br />
Right after that I get heavily involved in a pot and I’m pretty sure the guy has me beat but then I notice at the last second that we’re going to chop (read: share) the pot so I get over-excited after realizing this and kinda slap the dealer on the arm (who was sitting on my left) and say, “Hey! It’s a split-pot! It’s a split pot!” to which he turns around, glares at me and says, “YOU THINK?!?” Yikes. Again, I give a two dollar tip out of guilt. I then elect to change tables and play at Josh’s table where I quickly lose 340$ to end the day down $140. Ah nuts. <br />
<br />
However during the game, I half realize that Josh is less than 21 and isn’t legally allowed to gamble so I kinda look at him weird at one point and he tells me in French to call him Luke at the table. I figure it’s a fake I.D. thing but I keep forgetting cuz I get all excited at the poker table so I’m continuously referring to him in one hand as Luke and then Josh in the other. So he pulls me aside and tells me to pick one of the two names so it isn’t as obvious. He’s whispering this to me beside the poker pit boss guy who can’t really hear what we’re saying. I ask Josh, ‘hey where in Samhill did you get this Luke name anyway?” and he says it’s Luke Cornwell-Mott, his brother. So then like a total moron I say in full volume, “Oh is that what it says on your fake I.D.?!” Josh turns white as a ghost even though I find it to be funny. He’s losing money by the truckload so I don’t they’ll mind if he keeps playing. And they don’t.<br />
<br />
So 2pm sneaks up on me and I head back to make it for the LotR PSQ at 3pm. I have just enough time to run to MacDonalds and scarf down two double cheeseburgers (only a buck each!), a medium fries (gross, I ate like 3 of them) and a Hi-C. I barely make it back to the hotel before I’m running back to my hotel room for the bathroom (apparently my stomach is not too happy with my junk food diet), I run into Hayden (Wars Judge) in the hallway who says hi and I just say, “Macdonalds” as I run by and he says, “I understand.”<br />
<br />
I still make it to the PSQ on time somehow and it’ll be a five round festival with 29 players where the top 8 get premier points. I should have this one in the bag. Let’s hope my Gandalf culture fellowship can pull off lots of triple moves to nine and that my Gollum-based shadow can get some nice corruption wins and pull off lots of surprises with Horribly Strong.<br />
<br />
Round One<br />
Opponent: Ruben Reed<br />
Deck: Rohan-Gondor / Enduring Nazgul<br />
Good: This is a good match-up for me, especially my fellowship which has teched completely out against Enduring Nazgul since I heard lots of buzz on some broken Shapes Slowing Advancing or some crap like that which, as you’ll see, never shows up this weekend.<br />
Bad: I triple to site 4 against poor Ruben who didn’t get any minions in his combo-intensive shadow. This is the main power of my fellowship. With so many players using combo-intensive shadows (Enduring Nazgul, Beasterlings or even my horrific shadow build), having the ability to triple move at an opportunity is a HUGE win for your fellowship. I learned this from Mike Long in 2002 and never forgot it.<br />
Ugly: Shelob and Horribly Strong came down perfectly at site 6 to completely decimate his fellowship <br />
Result: FW shadow kill site 6<br />
1-0<br />
<br />
Round Two<br />
Opponent: Kaleb Michaud<br />
Deck: Dwarf / Enduring Nazgul<br />
Good: Kaleb was a relatively nice opponent. There was some issue about a takeback at some point that he got sore over but this is a PSQ and all and I had to practice my non-takebacks for tomorrow’s PSE since all my local play has softened me up.<br />
Bad: I didn’t get a single Saved by the Fire before the second sanctuary.<br />
Ugly: I was forced to triple to site 9 to win this game. Not easy.<br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
2-0 ! Off to a great start!<br />
<br />
Round Three<br />
Opponent: Ryan Connor<br />
Deck: Gondor-Gandalf / Threat Nazgul<br />
Good: Ryan’s a nice guy and we get a chance to chat while we are both deck-checked at the beginning of the round (it takes only 10 minutes and we still manage to finish before everyone else)<br />
Bad: I exhaust Gandalf at site 5 and am holding a Horribly Strong but can’t reconcile into a Gollum-fetcher at site 6 before he heals up. That’s pretty much game.<br />
Ugly: I’m forced to double to 7 because of this and am in great shape. Then Ryan drops Radagast and Grown Suddenly Tall at site 6 and triples to 9. DANG!<br />
Result: FL site 9<br />
2-1<br />
<br />
Round Four<br />
Opponent: Phil Edge<br />
Deck: Rohandalf – Underfoot bomb<br />
Good: This is my deck’s first swarm match in offline play. I’m anxious to see how I do.<br />
Bad: Cavern Entrance at site 9 prevents my Tale of Great Ring even though Phil almost forgets what Cavern Entrance does. <br />
Ugly: My shadow was NOT cooperating with me. I decided to run against this deck since I knew it needed a big set up. I double into nine and the extra twilight gets a massive amount of minions against my 5 companions and even with 3 servants I can’t survive.<br />
Result: FL site 9<br />
2-2<br />
<br />
Round Five<br />
Opponent: Bill O’Keeffe<br />
Deck: Rainbow fellowship / Dunland<br />
Good: Bill was an awesome opponent and a real nice guy<br />
Bad: Lots of mistakes were made by both of us in this game.<br />
Ugly: He moves to site 3 and I’m pretty sure I’m going to kill someone. I play the Pinnacle of Z site (dead wizard retriever) and manage to kill Gandalf. I then instantly regret playing the site but Bill doesn’t notice what the site does and forgets to play Gandalf back from his dead pile. Whoops.<br />
Result: FW shadow kill site 5<br />
3-2<br />
<br />
Well a 3-2 finish in a 29-player tournament doesn’t exactly net me top 8 so no premier points for me. At 95 premier points, I really want to hit 100 so all this little losses drive me bananas. And you know that the shimmer is bananas, b-a-n-a-n-a-s. <br />
<br />
So with the tournament over, I mosey on over to the Black Rider pre-release which is about to start it’s fourth round. At the top table pairing of who’s 3-0, I find my friend Matt Ward, Son of Chuck playing against this 12-year old girl, Meg Seymour. I’m all confused and say, “that girl is 3-0?!” to which her father, Jim, behind me says, “yep, that’s my daughter.” So I tell him that her journey is going to end right here since I consider Matt Ward to be a top player. Meg then proceeds to play card after card that Matt has to read since he doesn’t know any of the shadow pumps. Soon Frodo is at 8 burdens with lots of dead companions and he blocks some small minion whom Meg pumps up big time with some skirmish event and Matt extends his hand. Nice! I’m not going to let Matt live that one down. I should also mention that I am continuing to use the site marker that Matt Ward prepared for me last year. It is a character card that he designed for me, Patrick Sullivan, Drunken Canadian. It’s full of inside jokes regarding Bam opportunities with Josh and the like. Matt himself is using a baby anvil after he was refused at the airport to bring his real anvil on the plane. Too funny. <br />
<br />
So the guys and I head next door to the In & Out Burger joint for a late dinner. I get the double cheeseburger with onions and awful fries and we eat outside. It was the greasiest burger I’ve had in a while but pretty tasty. I’m not feeling too well so it’s an early bed for me. I pass out on the sofa bed and take so much room that by the time Paul Holbrook comes to crash, he’s too shy to move me and sleeps on the floor instead. <br />
<br />
<br />
Day One<br />
Saturday, March 12th, 2005<br />
“Good luck, man”<br />
<br />
Right so once again, an early wake-up but now I have far less time to kill until go time. So I head into the convention building which is housing the tournaments and wrangle Tim McKnight and playtesting designer extraordinaire, Mike Girard (also spokesperson for SoloFlex) into going to MacDonald’s for a delectable (thank you, Josh for introducing me to that adjective) McGriddle breakfast. And so we dined into the mid morning then rushed back for Round One of the PSE.<br />
<br />
Turns out that I get a bye for round One due to my high premier point total which is nice. 65 players with 27 of them getting first round byes. <br />
<br />
Round One:<br />
The Bye<br />
I squeaked out a win and we almost went to time<br />
1-0<br />
<br />
Round: Two<br />
Opponent: Michael Perruca, son of Steve. One of three father-child teams present in Vegas (Chuck and Matt, Meg and Jim being the other two) <br />
Deck: Dwarf-Smeagol / Morc Swarm<br />
Good: This was a good match-up for me since I am packing lots of skirmish events and Terrible and Evil and my ring-bearer has a high strength. <br />
Bad: Not only do I NOT draw into Saved by the Fire until site 6 but I also don’t draw a SINGLE minion until site 6.<br />
Ugly: Because I finally draw into Saved by the Fire at 6, that means I flood the pool moving into 7 instead of flooding moving into 2 or 3. So not only does a massive swarm hit the table but Sauron, The Lord of the Rings decides to join the party as well.<br />
Result: FL shadow kill site 7<br />
Seeing a top-player like Michael play this deck is incredibly frustrating since I was playing this same deck a couple months ago and gave it up. But if Perruca is playing it, then it must be better than I thought so I’m thinking I made the wrong deck choice.<br />
1-1<br />
<br />
Round: Three<br />
Opponent: Jim Seymour, father to Meg<br />
Deck: Corsair / Gandwarf<br />
Good: Jim was a real nice opponent.<br />
Bad: I get out my Roll of Thunder at site 8 against his boats<br />
Ugly: My shadow did absolutely nothing yet again<br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
2-1<br />
<br />
Round: Four<br />
Opponent: Phil Edge...again<br />
Deck: Same, Underfoot bomb with Rohandalf<br />
Good: I’m pretty decent at rematches since my experience will get me far in terms of making the right choices this time around.<br />
Bad: I decide to NOT race against the Underfoot bomb this time around and managed to Roll of Thunder THREE boats and New Awakened, Deep in Thought and Treebeard away all his They are Coming and Underfoots. However, I don’t double into nine because I think, for some reason, that I can kill his exhausted fellowship with my two Horribly Strongs in hand.<br />
Ugly: He plays Eowyn, Lady of Rohan at site 7 and doubles into nine. I kill everyone except Isildur getting him to 8 burdens when he has 9 resistance. D’oh!<br />
Result: FL site 9<br />
2-2<br />
<br />
At this point, I need to win the next 3 rounds to make Day Two. Winning out is my thing... I hope.<br />
<br />
Round: Five<br />
Opponent: From Colorado, the table-flipping madman, Matt Riecks<br />
Deck: Rohandalf / Beasterlings<br />
Good: I finally get a funny opponent. Matt is making pretty funny jokes during the whole match which is totally my favourite play environment.<br />
Bad: I don’t draw into a single minion until site 7 again. I’m starting to think my deck is jank.<br />
Ugly: He doesn’t get his Grown Suddenly Tall until after site 9. Yay for me.<br />
Result: FL site 9 – his shadow was just to tough and it scared me too much to double move. I’m playing like a real chicken and am losing games because of it.<br />
2-3 <br />
<br />
Well, I’m out of Day Two so I can just have some fun at this time.<br />
<br />
Round: Six<br />
Opponent: Jacob Oss<br />
Deck: Who knows? He got Hungry so he bid 16.<br />
Good: Having time to go eat.<br />
Bad: Not getting to play.<br />
Ugly: I went to get 2 double cheeseburgers at MacDonald’s showing that I don’t learn from my mistakes<br />
Result: FW site 1<br />
3-3<br />
<br />
Round: Seven<br />
Opponent: Erik Cabanero<br />
Deck: Dworcs<br />
Good: This was an awesome match since I get along with Gharret so well. Totally relaxed since we were both out of contention for Day Two. Steve Jones is playing right on my left doing his incredible Kip (from Napoleon Dynamite) impressions (i.e. playing a huge swarm and saying with a lisp, “that’s what I’m talkin’ about.”)<br />
Bad: I got out all 4 Horribly Strong before site 7<br />
Ugly: He has Aragorn, Durin and Gimli against Shelob and Gollum. I played out my minions and was so certain that I was going to corrupt Gimli that Noda got my traditional, “Good luck, man” after I finished my shadow phase. <br />
Result: FW shadow corruption site 7<br />
4-3<br />
<br />
So bad news is I don’t make day two. I finish right in front of Mike Noonan and right behind Luke Cornwell-Mott. Good news is that this is my FIRST winning record in Vegas over 3 years. This is always my worst performance area so I’m glad to know that I didn’t pull another 3-5.  I end up winning lots of foreign packs and a Bust of Merry which I don’t really have any strong need for so I give it to Shane’s daughter. Shane was one of the DGMA judges. He has this bright-eyed little angel who drew me a picture J<br />
<br />
So it’s pretty early at this point and I’ve missed Paul Holbrook’s Black Rider release so I go and watch a few games that the only other Montreal resident present in Vegas is playing. Yannick Lapointe, SW:CCG guru, is trying to get into Day Three Wars after getting 9th in Day One (you need to make top 8 in day one or day two). So he wins 100$ for 9th but he just wants to make day three. Anyway, he seems to be winning his game and it’s really fun to watch Wars games being played by top players. Note that these are all draft games and Kyle Craft went undefeated on Day One (I watched a couple of his games too). Both he and Yannick have opposing drafting strategies (Kyle is partial to Blue Space decks and Yannick is all over the Red Space deck). I used to play Star Wars back in the day and it was fun to watch force draining and all that noise. <br />
<br />
So I’m lucky enough to catch Tim McKnight leaving to the Rio along with someguy I keep calling Jeff who isn’t actually named Jeff and I still can’t remember his dang name. Anyway it’s his car and Chris Cole, Will Dineaga and Kyle Craft join us as well. We try out the Rio’s buffet since we heard good things and it ends up being the best buffet I’ve ever had in my life. We walk through the casino a little first and find a BlackJack section were the dealers are wearing bikinis (female dealers, by the way) and I don’t care how much money I’m going to lose, I think I’ll play at those tables after we eat. <br />
<br />
So we stuff our faces with ribs, steaks, Chinese food, salad, Gelato, sushi, mashed potatoes, you name it. I order a coke which is constantly getting refilled and Kyle Craft orders a chocolate milk. The waiter says, “oh no, you don’t want that.” Kyle says, “why not?” And he says, “cuz we have to make those by hand and it’s a lot of work. And you know, it’s just chocolate syrup in milk.” Kyle answers, “of course it is. That’s exactly what I want.” The waiter then grumbles off and mixes Kyle’s chocolate milk. Kyle then says how much work it is to reach into his wallet and pull out tip money and he hopes he’ll have the energy for it when the bill comes. <br />
<br />
Speaking of the bill, you have to use this automated teller which makes this LOUD noise when you payment is accepted. Everytime it did its 90-decibel DING!, the guy who I called Jeff-who-isn’t-Jeff would yell out WINNAH! It was pretty funny.<br />
<br />
So then we run into Seth Maser, Steve Jones, Bryce Stevenson, Bill, Matt Riecks and we get the heck out of there. On the way out, we check the Blackjack tables with the bikinis and they are all 25 or 50 dollar tables so forget that noise. <br />
<br />
We then get over to the Excalibur where Tim, Chris and the others and I all play Blackjack where we all get wiped out except for Tim who’s conservative nature pays off. We then hit up the poker room and all finish up I think. I got all my Blackjack losses back and finished up 50 bucks or so. <br />
<br />
Back to the Hampton Inn Tropicana and the boys are playtesting in the adjacent room. Thomas Mitchell, who is the 17th seed and 1st alternative player likes his chances of playing in Day Two so he stays up playtesting fairly late. I go into my room and spot his girlfriend, Pam, sleeping in MY bed so I go back into their room and hijack one of their beds (I think it was either Will Dineaga or Bill’s bed. Either way, not a big deal). <br />
<br />
<br />
Day Two<br />
Sunday, March 13th, 2005<br />
Something Hayden wanted me to say but I forgot goes here<br />
<br />
So I wake up around 9ish or so and no one has grabbed the extra spot in the bed. Everyone is glaring at me telling me I snored all night but I don’t really feel bad until I start passing mad gas in the morning much to their chagrin. As I’m getting up, a very tired and very drunk Courtney Haggerty and Dr Jason Jones stumbles into the door after their full night of galavanting around Vegas. Dr. Jones falls dead asleep in the sofa bed I just got out of and Courtney collapses on some bed somewhere. <br />
<br />
I run over to McGriddleland for another installment of Colon Blow Special Combo and race back since I want to watch round one of both the LotR PSE and the Wars Day Three. Every WARS player has already won at least 250$ (Yannick is at 350$) and if they make it through their first round, they win 400$ at least (500$ for Yannick). Either Kyle or Yannick gets paired up against Alan Sagan from Vancouver which I’m upset about since I want all three of them to move on. So I can’t watch the game since I don’t know who to root for. <br />
<br />
So I go off to the LotR side of the hall and Mike Ium hasn’t shown up yet so Thomas Mitchell is already to rock the vote when Ium walks in at the 11th hour (is that the correct expression? Or is it 13th hour? I can never remember). Anyway, I get geared up to play in the World Cup qualifier since I might go to Essen again if I’m feeling lucky and start to look for teammates. I get some pretty hilarious offers (read: Steve Jones) but the original plan was Steve Jones, Mike Noonan and myself would wear our tuxes and go as Team TuxedoFace but both of them dropped out so forget than jank. In the end, I snatch up Michael Perruca (excellent draft choice) and Matt Riecks (horrible draft choice, almost as bad as their decision to play with me given the weekend I was having). So the three of us form the elite Team KwyjiboKardz who has never lost a team event.... evah! <br />
<br />
We bust out the t-shirts and get to work. Steve forms a team with Bryce and Mike and that’s the only Team (Team Revolution) that we’re actually slightly worried about... but not really.<br />
<br />
Round: One<br />
Opponent: Tim McIntosh<br />
Deck: Knights n’ Corsairs<br />
Good:  I had a very nice start to my shadow for once<br />
Bad: I double to 3 for NO reason. I wasn’t set up at all and Castamir and Halberd come out and kills enough companions to make Treebeard unplayable (since I have to spot 3 ALIVE Gandalf companions)<br />
Ugly: At site 4, Castamir and Halberd comes out again and I can’t risk losing Gandalf so I take the risk of blocking with Frodo and using up my Tale of Great Ring and he has the Wind that Sped Ships to overwhelm my crappy ring-bearer.<br />
Result: FL shadow kill site 4<br />
0-1<br />
Matt plays Meg Seymour and wins 1-0<br />
Michael plays Bryce S and wins 1-0<br />
Team is 2-1<br />
<br />
Round: Two<br />
Opponent: Mike Noonan<br />
Deck: Noble Leaders / Corsairs<br />
Good: It’s Mike!<br />
Bad: Yet again, no Saved from the Fire ALL game<br />
Ugly: My Frodo is strength 8 thanks to There & Back Again, Gandalf (LotC) and 2 G for Grand, so I block a 14 strength Nemenorian with Halberd and say pass. I have a Servant of the Secret Fire in hand. Mike then tells me that the site is Hand Weapons +2 so his minion is 16. I don’t even attempt to ask for a takeback cuz I’ve been playing so badly so I just scoop. <br />
Result: FL Shadow Kill site 5<br />
0-2 (wonderful)<br />
Matt plays Tim (the guy I just played) and gets a Timed Loss! AHHH  1-1<br />
Michael Perruca plays some kid and gets a full win 2-0<br />
Team is 3-3 YUCK<br />
<br />
Round: Three<br />
Opponent: Derrick Hilger<br />
Deck: Elf Archery with Beasterlings<br />
Good: This was a real nice relaxed game<br />
Bad: His combo-intensive shadow hurt him badly<br />
Ugly: I used Terrible & Evil to get rid of Easterling Captains before they added the burdens and then once he did, I simply used Sent Back to get rid of a loaded Captain. <br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
1-2<br />
Michael played some guy and won 3-0<br />
Matt played Steve Jones and lost I think 1-2 <br />
Team is 5-4<br />
<br />
Round: Four<br />
Opponent: quiet and reserved Meg Seymour<br />
Deck: Sauron Grind / Elf-Gondor<br />
Good: Nice girl. All quiet and calculating all the time. <br />
Bad: I triple move to 6 and then triple to 9 since her fellowship was untouchable.<br />
Ugly: She doesn’t use Radagast’s gametext even though she’s clogged with fellowship since I’m not playing minions. I don’t think she knew about Radagast’s gametext and I wasn’t about to spill the beans cuz I’m a big meanie.<br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
2-2<br />
Michael Perruca delivers the mail against some kid and goes 4-0<br />
Matt Riecks plays against young Zeke and pulls it off 2-2<br />
So the team finishes 8-4 which ties us for first place but we lose on strength of schedule so we get 2nd place in the tournament. NOOOOOO!<br />
<br />
I win some packs and foils and some collector plate which I once again have no use for so I give it to the Seymours since their team came in dead last I think. <br />
<br />
So I go to watch WARS top 8 in which both Kyle Craft and Yannick Lapointe are squaring off against one another. Yannick has received the Godliest of drafts this time around and he doesn’t see how he can lose since this final draft determines the top player. Kyle is half upset with his draft and is half-confident. They proceed to play and Yannick’s first 6 destiny draws are ALL zero. This is enough to turn the tide and Kyle Craft manages to win by only 6 force (read: energy)! Which means if just one of those destiny draws had turned out better, it would have likely been a very different game. Kyle goes on to nab second place and a healthy pot. <br />
<br />
I follow some of the LotR PSE day two action but am disappointed to see both Mike Ium and Casey Barson eliminated. Mike’s game was funny since Josh “SlowRoll” Cornwell-Mott was watching it with me and Seth kept yelling at Josh. It was too funny. I then try to glance at what this Colnel Pierre Marie character (who looks just like Gimli) is playing. He’s again playing that pesky Dwarf-Smeagol/Morc deck that I used to play and obviously should have stuck with. I watched a few seconds of his game against Franklin Kenter and a few seconds is all I need to watch Franklin get swarmed twice in a row at site 3. It must have scared the crap out of him losing that fast. The fellowship came to such a sudden and violent stop at site 3 that it left skids at the sanctuary.<br />
<br />
Decipher then announces that they will run a final sealed deck Black Rider release event and it will be free! Not only that, but all players that finish it will receive a foil Beastly Olog-Hai from the French PSE. Nice! So I sign up and then run out to the In & Out Burger with Bryce, Steve Jones, Will Dineaga, Bill, Mike Noonan and a few others. I grab two cheeseburgers and pass on the fries this time around but instead of getting a Lemonade, I elect for the Vanilla Shake. This ends up being a poor strategic play. <br />
Anyway we’re all sitting outside and this really cute middle-aged woman is having an afternoon delight lunch with her husband behind us. She starts walking to her car after they’re finished and I make a comment, “hey guys, check out the Milk,” except I didn’t say Milk. Bryce’s eyes go all big as he looks at me (and slightly over me) in amazement saying, “Oh snap.” And Steve Jones turns his head away from me, covering his face and saying, “lalalalala.” So I’m all like “what?” Then the looming shadow of her husband passes over me as he finishes emptying his tray into the garbage bin right beside me. Yikes. That was pretty embarrassing.<br />
<br />
Anyway, back to the tournament hall. I join the very last pre-release and get an Aragorn Shadows starter. I’m crazy mad since I want Black Rider product even though the Aragorn starter is the second best starter of the 6 available. So I talk Dr. Jason Jones into trading his Saruman starter with me for the Aragorn starter. I might not win now but at least I get to play some Black Rider cards.  I get some pretty MAD pulls (in the starter, I get the rare Mouth of Sauron) and in the Shadows starters I pulled Strider, Lurtz, Gollum AND foil Legolas! Incredible. <br />
<br />
Round: One<br />
Opponent: Clayton Edwards<br />
Deck: Evil Men with Rohan – Black Rider<br />
Good:  This was a relaxed but slow game<br />
Bad: I double to 3 for no real reason and lose Farmer Maggot<br />
Ugly: At site 8 I’m pretty messed up but I have 3 pumps for Frodo and I play a Ranger to play Caras as site 9. BAM!<br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
1-0<br />
<br />
Round: Two<br />
Opponent: Julien Rios (mike ium’s day two PSE first casualty, Julien is also a witness to my ‘Milk’ incident at the In&Out Burger)<br />
Deck: Evil Men with Rohan – Black Rider<br />
Good: I had very good fellowship draws<br />
Bad: At 9 I had the perfect cards, two pumps for Frodo and then a triple to Overwhelm event<br />
Ugly: He also draws Lurtz and plays him at Emyn Muil to make him fierce! Ouch<br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
2-0<br />
<br />
<br />
Round: Three<br />
Opponent: Robert Dayton<br />
Deck: Mirror match<br />
Good: Last game cuz I’m tired<br />
Bad: Chris S from Cali sneaks up behind us and starts doing his Steve Irwin imitation (you know, that alligator guy). He basically giving us a running commentary on every card that is being played like it was wildlife that Steve was watching. I know it probably doesn’t sound funny here but I guarantee that it was the single funniest thing I had heard all year. Bryce, myself and others around us were all in stitches. We were picturing Steve Irwin leading the fellowship into Moria and making comments on how the Watcher in the Water is “a beautiful Cree‘Cha” and such. Totally hilarious. <br />
Ugly: After about 4 minutes of us clowing around, my opponent asks me to hurry up since he doesn’t want to time out. I ask the judge how much time is left and he says 40 minutes, and I’m at like site 4 or 5. Holy cow...<br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
3-0<br />
<br />
So I tie for first and get bumped on strength of schedule. I win an uncut sheet which I ask Will to redraw since I don’t really have any use for uncut sheets. The prize support is excellent nonetheless. <br />
<br />
So ends the LotR playing of Vegas. I wasn’t quite sick of it but I certainly was tired. I say my goodbyes to the gang and since I’m not in the mood to have my bed janked from me again, I accept an awesome offer from the Utah gang (Casey, Hags and Jason) to stay with them at the Orleans. So we leave together in Jason’s wicked Lexus, get jacked on the room rate and then hit up the Courtyard Café for a bite. Everyone orders a ton of food but I’m insanely ill from the In&Out Burger which is causing me physical pain at this point so I just order soup and ice cream (I’m an idiot). We then hit up the poker room there and the dealers are way cool. I win either 50 or 150 (I can’t remember) at the 2-4 table which is insanely dull to play at but at least you don’t lose any money. Then we’re supposed to stay up to go bowling and do all sorts of fun stuff but after one whiskey, it’s 3AM and I’m tired as heck. So Casey and I go up to bed while Hags and Jason stay up until 8 or so. <br />
<br />
Casey and I flip on the TV and A Few Good Men is playing. We get all into it since it’s such a good movie even though Demi Moore is the worst actress ever. Still, we only last 5 minutes into it before we’re both sound asleep.<br />
<br />
<br />
Last Day<br />
Monday, March 14th, 2005<br />
Ron Burgundy is no Larry David<br />
<br />
So we all sleep in to about 11 being completely exhausted. I have to shake Jason and Hags awake since Jason is playing in a no-limit tournament at 12 and Hags and Casey need to get me to the airport. I run down to get a moka frappuccino at Seattle’s Best Coffee for Jason since he needs the alertness for the tournament. I wonder how he did? Anyway, Casey, Courtney and I take off to the airport blasting Gwen Stefani at full volume which I thought was ok at the time and haven’t been able to get out of my head ever since. That was the fastest 0.99$ I spent on iTunes evah.<br />
<br />
So I wait in this gigantic line at the airport only for them to tell me at the end of it that I’m in the wrong line since I’m Canadian and we have our “own line.” I’m like what?! If you prick me, do I not bleed aboot the place like the rest of ya, eh? <br />
<br />
Anyway, my flight gets delayed by 40 minutes which stresses me out to no end since my connection leaves 45 minutes after my scheduled arrival in Philly. How am I going to make my connection? How is my baggage going to make it home? So the ulcer starts flaring up and I need to relax so I go to rent an InMotion DVD playah with 2 DVDs. I rent Anchorman (since Vera Drake isn’t out yet) and Season 3 of Curb Your Enthusiasm (since The Office was out). Let it be said that renting comedies isn’t the best idea when you’re by yourself on an airplane. <br />
<br />
So I still have time to kill so I play the Wheel of Fortune slot machine which gave me 400$ 2 years ago and this time it sucks down my 50$ in 2 minutes. So I’m down to my last C-note and I try shoving it into the slot machine to make some money. I try 3 times but it won’t take my hundred-dollar bill so I take it as a sign to save it for a rainy day. <br />
<br />
I watch the premier of Season 3 of Curb Your Enthusiasm first (episode where Larry buys Ted Danson a cream-colored shirt inspired by a widow’s dead husband’s picture). This was a mistake. It was so funny that it raised the bar far too high to properly enjoy Anchorman. Although I almost pulled a Franklin Kenter when I watched the bloopers. <br />
<br />
I get into Philly 5 minutes before my flight to Montreal and race the wrong way down the concourse trying to find me gate. I then race all the way back and make it into the flight. The flight is 79% empty and I’m all disoriented from running around and being stressed out that my luggage is never going to make it. So I find an old woman in my assigned seat and I make a big deal about her to get out. She kinda looks at me weird since there is like 140 free seats everywhere. The flight attendant comes by and tells me that I can just sit anywhere. So everyone is looking at me strange as I go, “oh.” So I just grab my stuff and sit in the back of the plane laughing out loud watching DVDs by myself like a crazy person.<br />
<br />
I arrive in Montreal and get to the now infamous Customs officer with whom I always have issues. In January, when I came back from Spain and Austria, they searched ALL my bags. So the kid asks me this time where I stayed in Vegas and I stumble over the answer since I stayed in more than one hotel, “um... well last night was in Orleans but the other ones was Hampton Tropicana... uh...yeah.” So he writes some notes on my little paper and says, “show this to the guy on the way out.” I’m like all mad cuz I figure he wrote the secret code that lets the guy go all Deliverance on me. So before I get out I have to retrieve my baggage..... which never shows up. So I fill out a missing luggage form and give them a phone number to reach me. They want a number that will likely have me answer so I give my cell number (not realizing at the time that my cell phone is in Philadelphia somewhere in the baggage claim). I then pass the Customs guy who checks my little sign-out sheet and I’m ready to deck him right in the swingers if he doesn’t let me through, but he does so I’m happy to get a break there.<br />
<br />
So I get outside and it’s FREEZING. Remember that jacket I wore on the way to Vegas? Well, it is also in Philly in my luggage. So it’s 1 in the morning in Montreal and I’m waiting for the bus to my car. I finally get in and help a mom (no jokes here) get her kid and baby stroller on the bus since I DESPERATELY need brownie points and better karma at this point. The guy drops me off by my car and drives off. It is bitterly cold outside and it’s the dead of night. I search everywhere before realizing that my car keys are also in my luggage. So luckily, one of the very very few skills I have is that I’m a regular MacGyver. With a credit card, I not only manage to break into my car but I actually start the engine with it too. Remind me to show you guys how you do this with a Honda Civic sometime. It’s pretty cool. <br />
<br />
So I drive home and once again realize that I don’t have anyway to get into my house. So I ring my neighboor’s doorbell and Rachel answers the door (thankfully still awake at 1am) and lets me into my house (swapping house keys is the best thing evah). <br />
<br />
Then I go to bed. <br />
<br />
The End<br />
<br />
Props<br />
·	Kirk England for letting me into his wedding party and getting this whole thing put together<br />
·	Heather for marrying a gamer. I hope there’s more like you out there<br />
·	Steve Jones for arranging the hotel rooms and such and for doing that Kip imitation all weekend. That never got old. I love you :)<br />
·	Jason Jones for the invite to the Orleans and offering a bed and a ride. Hmm... that doesn’t sound good at all.<br />
·	Hags for bein’ cool<br />
·	Barson for keeping a cool head about the decklist error and continuing to have fun<br />
·	Decipher for 60 minute rounds. I have NEVER had such relaxed games in a PSE<br />
·	Phil Edge for beating me TWICE with that pesky deck (play faster tho, we don’t want another Tennet)<br />
·	Michael Perruca for being the heavyweight on my team. We’ll get ‘em next time, champ<br />
·	Steve Perruca for playing the same game his son plays. I can’t really express how awesome that is. I miss my dad L<br />
·	Jim and Meg for playing the game for fun and nothing else (especially Meg cuz she’s better than Jim J<br />
·	Matt Ward for trying to get a full sized anvil on an airplane<br />
·	Matt Riecks for being on my team and playing as badly as I did<br />
·	Jacob Oss for giving me a full win so I could eat<br />
·	Gharret Noda for letting me continuously call him Erik and laughing at my other stupid jokes<br />
·	Chris S for giving me the BEST laugh of 2005 so far<br />
·	*takes deep breath* Seth Maser for playing the best he’s ever played but mostly for singing that hilarious Randy Newman Family Guy song. You do that perfectly<br />
·	Mike Noonan for wearing a white-tie tux and for being lots of fun all weekend<br />
·	Josh for having cool hair and terrible jogging pants<br />
·	Mike Ium for always making me laugh and talking just like Kip from Napoleon Dynamite except not on-purpose<br />
·	Chris Cole for the double-barreled shotgun flipoff<br />
·	Tim McKnight for knowing that the order of my props list has absolutely no bearing on the importance of the individuals listed therein<br />
·	Will Dineaga for trying to get me to pronounce yee-ah<br />
·	Mike Girard for always smilin’<br />
·	Hayden cuz he asked me to<br />
·	Matt Clemans for running an excellent event. Tough call on the decklist thing but I’m sure only good will come from it. Hope I can still stay with you for Origins J<br />
·	Yannick and Kyle for kickin’ butt in WARS<br />
·	Alan & Sheri for comin’ out from B.C. to play<br />
·	I’m gonna have to say Richard Peiper for stealing my mojo and doing something awesome with it<br />
<br />
<br />
Slops<br />
·	Pam for stealing MY bed. <br />
·	Tournament Guidelines for not being clear enough that excellent judges are unable to do their job properly<br />
·	Chris Williams for being Christianized (at least you’re happy)<br />
·	Zach Shephard and Dan Jones for not being there (ha!)<br />
·	Me for forgetting that guy’s name who I kept calling Jeff who isn’t really Jeff<br />
·	U.S. Airways for charging me to eat, to listen to their terrible movies and then losing my luggage<br />
·	Me IF I forgot anyone that deserves to be on either of these two lists<br />
